Description

Henry Edward Foster was elected to the City Council at a by-election in 1927. A plumber who had risen through the trade union movement to become secretary of the Trades Hall Council in 1923, Foster's presence on the City Council marked a new presence in local government for the Australian Labor Party. While the ALP had largely ignored the City of Melbourne elections, dominated by city businessmen and mostly devoid of working-class voters, Foster's candidature was an opportunity to secure Labor power if grand plans for a Greater Melbourne Council came to fruition.

Description

After inheriting ownership and control of the prominent hardware firm McEwan's aged just 23, Harold Daniel Luxton ascended rapidly in Melbourne business circles. Elected to the City Council in 1919, Luxton became the youngest ever Lord Mayor in 1928 and served an extraordinary three consecutive terms. In addition to sitting on the Council until 1943, Luxton sat in the Victorian Parliament between 1930 and 1935. Famously, in later life, Luxton lamented that Melbourne had become a "deadly dull" city as a result of its restrictive liquor laws.
Link: Harold Daniel Luxton, ADB

Description

A city businessman of many interests and long-standing councillor since 1913, by 1925 Brunton had served three terms as Lord Mayor. He had risen to considerable public prominence when, during the 1923 police strike, he had used untested municipal powers to recruit a force of special constables and ordered them to bring rioting and looting under control on behalf of the Council's business owner constituents. In 1925, Brunton was also the architect of a new scheme for a Greater Melbourne Council - which, like previous attempts, was defeated.
Link: Sir William Brunton, ADB

Description

Charles George Watts followed his father into the staff of the City Council as a junior clerk in 1886. He was appointed City Treasurer in 1922 and retained the office until his retirement in 1936.

Description

George Henry Claude Crespin succeeded his father, Godwin George Crespin, for a seat on the City Council in 1917. In 1925, he had recently been appointed to the position of Alderman - a senior councillor for the ward, with an extended seven-year term.

Description

Lloyd was a managing director of the Bourke Street department store Buckley and Nunn. He had been newly elected to the City Council in 1925.
Link: Buckley and Nunn @ eMelbourne

Description

Inside the Town Clerk's office, the Chief Clerk supervised around ten other clerks to carry out the administrative work of the City Council. Most senior were the Lord Mayor and Town Clerk's personal secretaries; most junior the assisting stationery clerk.
